    "nypl_url": "https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/2db39620-c54e-012f-d2c1-58d385a7bc34",
    "original_title": "Manhattan: Greenwich Street - Albany Street",
    "rotation": 90,
    "text": "(1)\n\nGreenwich Street, west side, north from Albany Street, showing at the N.W. corner a 3\u00bd-story building formerly known as the Planters Hotel. This building No. 122 Greenwich Street, was for a time a dry goods store; patronized by Henry Clay and other celebrities. Overhead, on Greenwich Street, is the Ninth Ave. Elevated Line.\nMay 1925.\n\nEugene L. Armbruster Collection.\n\n(2)\n\nThe same.\nMay 1925.\n\nEugene L. Armbruster Collection.\n\n(3)\n\nA view eastward on Albany Street, and showing the side of the former Planters Hotel. From that point, to the immediate foreground appear; No. 3 (2-story structure); Nos. 5 and 7; all on Albany Street. Across Greenwich Street, appears the Hamilton Building, No. 125-131 Greenwich Street, at the S.E. corner of Thames Street.\nMay 1925.\n\nEugene L. Armbruster Collection.\n\n(4)\n\nThe same, at a later date.\nMay 4th, 1941.\n\nP.L. Sperr.\n",
    "text_source": "gpt",
    "thumb_url": "https://www.oldnyc.org/rotated-assets/thumb/720187f-a.90.jpg",
    "title": "",
    "width": 409,
    "years": [
      "1925"
    ]
